# DISTILLED PRINCIPLES — the project-AGNOSTIC layer (DESIGN.md §6/§8/§11).
# This is the "refined" output: each decision's transferable LAW, with every project noun,
# path, library, model name, code number and parameter value stripped out (those live in the
# per-project facts/plan as "just an instance"). The join key `id` matches plan.<proj>.jsonl
# `principle` and quiz.jsonl. Maturity (how many independent instances a law has survived, how
# many verified) is DERIVED from the plans at render time — it is NOT stored here, so this file
# stays project-free. fields: id | family | law
{"id":"frozen-component-contract","family":"Frozen contract & reuse","law":"A frozen/pretrained component has an exact input contract; any preprocessing that differs from what it was trained on — even a library default — silently maps inputs out of distribution."}
{"id":"dont-retrain-a-working-frozen-piece","family":"Frozen contract & reuse","law":"Don't retrain a component that already works under its contract; add the new behavior elsewhere — retraining it under a changed contract tends to regress it."}
{"id":"reuse-verified-reference","family":"Frozen contract & reuse","law":"Patch a verified reference implementation for the SAME problem; don't fork code written for a different problem just because it is nearby."}
{"id":"train-infer-parity","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"The loss must align indices exactly as inference consumes them; an off-by-one between prediction and target teaches a degenerate copy."}
{"id":"in-place-not-shifted","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"Align the loss to how THIS objective consumes positions; blindly copying another regime's index convention silently corrupts the objective."}
{"id":"majority-class-loss-weight-sets-behavior","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"When one target class dominates the positions, its loss weight — not the sampling temperature — decides whether the rare behavior is ever learned; defaults under-train the minority."}
{"id":"weight-loss-by-mask-rate","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"Weight the loss so the decisive-but-sparse regime isn't drowned out by the voluminous-but-easy regime."}
{"id":"beware-the-trivially-predictable-majority","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"An aggregate metric can be dominated by a trivially-predictable majority (silence/padding/copy-previous); split it by region or the number hides the part that matters."}
{"id":"info-set-must-match-deployment-causality","family":"Information set & leakage","law":"Train a component on the same information set it will have at deployment; if training sees context inference can't (e.g. the future), outputs go out of distribution when deployed."}
{"id":"diffusion-needs-bidirectional-attention","family":"Information set & leakage","law":"The attention/information mask must give each position the context its objective requires to predict; hiding required context collapses the method to a degenerate one."}
{"id":"no-cross-sample-leak","family":"Information set & leakage","law":"When an attention mask becomes less restrictive, re-audit packing: positions may now attend across sample/document boundaries the stricter mask used to prevent."}
{"id":"eval-conditions-must-equal-deployment","family":"Eval realism","law":"An eval that hands the model help deployment won't have (a crutch quietly solving the hardest sub-task) reports a number that is a lie; eval conditions must equal deployment."}
{"id":"free-running-not-teacher-forced-is-the-test","family":"Eval realism","law":"Teacher-forced metrics only test local one-step continuation; the real test is free-running generation, which compounds errors and exposes collapse."}
{"id":"eval-matches-done-bar","family":"Eval realism","law":"Measure with the metric that reflects the actual done-bar; the training loss can keep falling while the quality you care about does not improve."}
{"id":"verify-data-before-blaming-algorithm","family":"Data integrity","law":"Rule out corrupted/leaked/skewed data before blaming the method; bad data produces failures that masquerade as model bugs and silently caps the ceiling."}
{"id":"dedup-on-the-full-identity-key","family":"Data integrity","law":"Deduplicate train/val on the full identity key, not a coarse id; a coarse key scatters pieces of one item across both splits and inflates eval."}
{"id":"data-must-contain-the-behavior-you-want","family":"Data integrity","law":"A model can only learn a behavior from data that actually contains it; if the target phenomenon isn't in the data, no training will conjure it."}
{"id":"hparams-dont-transfer-across-regimes","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"Hyperparameters (especially LR) are regime-specific; a value tuned for one training regime steps too big or small in another and diverges or overfits."}
{"id":"low-lr-for-continued-pretrain","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"Continued training from already-converged weights needs a low LR with warmup; a from-scratch LR shocks the prior — and the schedule must be written into config, not left to a launcher default."}
{"id":"anneal-not-shock","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"When adapting pretrained weights to a new objective/structure, anneal the change over a warmup so the prior bends instead of being shocked away; validate transfer with an init-vs-random ablation."}
{"id":"fresh-not-continued-when-the-design-changed","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"When the design/loss/data changed, start fresh from a clean base; continuing a prior experimental checkpoint carries its rot forward."}
{"id":"init-from-the-capable-checkpoint-when-adding-behavior","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"When adding a behavior on top of intact capability, init from the checkpoint that already has the capability; a bare base re-learns it wastefully, a rotted one carries garbage forward."}
{"id":"verify-init-checkpoint-loads","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"Confirm the intended init checkpoint actually exists and loads in the needed form before building on it; availability/shape assumptions are load-bearing and cheap to check first."}
{"id":"small-additive-signal-gets-swamped","family":"Architecture wiring","law":"A learned signal added at a magnitude far below the signals it rides on gets swamped; conditioning needs comparable magnitude or its own parameters."}
{"id":"clean-role-delimited-turn-layout","family":"Architecture wiring","law":"Reuse the existing role/turn-delimiting machinery rather than inventing a new axis; the model must unambiguously know whose signal is whose and when its turn starts."}
{"id":"a-gate-copied-across-regimes-misfires","family":"Architecture wiring","law":"A gate/mask copied from one regime encodes that regime's premise; reused where the premise no longer holds, it silently does the wrong thing."}
{"id":"backward-is-the-memory-bottleneck","family":"Compute, config & diagnosis","law":"The backward pass (grads+activations) sets the memory peak and scales with per-device batch; reach a large effective batch by accumulating gradients, not by stacking per-device."}
{"id":"batch-and-parallel-fit","family":"Compute, config & diagnosis","law":"Batch size, sequence length and the parallelism strategy must be chosen for the actual model size and memory pattern, which shifts when the architecture changes."}
{"id":"config-from-many-sources-silently-overrides","family":"Compute, config & diagnosis","law":"When multiple layers can set the same config, one silently wins; print the EFFECTIVE value, because what you wrote may not be what runs."}
{"id":"rule-out-the-trunk-before-blaming-a-branch","family":"Compute, config & diagnosis","law":"Before blaming a specific design choice (a branch), rule out a trunk fault (under-training, a preprocessing bug); the symptom often isn't where you're looking."}
{"id":"block-size-tradeoff","family":"Method design space","law":"Expose the knob that interpolates between two regimes explicitly; its setting trades parallelism/throughput against staying close to the known-good regime."}
{"id":"masked-absorbing-diffusion","family":"Method design space","law":"Prefer the formulation that reuses the pretrained head/vocab so prior weights transfer; a formulation that discards the pretrained head throws the init away."}
{"id":"noise-schedule-choice","family":"Method design space","law":"The sampling/corruption schedule decides which regimes the model trains on and interacts with the loss weighting; choose it deliberately, don't inherit a default."}
{"id":"iterative-unmask-decoding","family":"Method design space","law":"Decoding is a design space (order, steps-per-unit, stopping rule); pin these explicitly — they, not just the trained weights, determine output quality."}
# ── Mined principles (trainlint-builder): distilled from voidrank/llm_agent_quant2 + audio model/codec repos (moshi/encodec/lhotse/icefall). Each repro-PROVEN; provenance in principles.mined.jsonl ──
{"id":"respect-point-in-time-no-lookahead","family":"Information set & leakage","law":"A value used at decision time t must be the value actually known/realized at t, under one consistent time convention; an off-by-one window edge (an inclusive bound padded +1), a fill credited at the START of its execution window instead of when it clears, or an open-vs-close timestamp mismatch between two stages all silently leak the future or shift the series one period."}
{"id":"window-end-must-track-source-coverage","family":"Information set & leakage","law":"Set a data window's end to the source's actual last-covered timestamp, not wall-clock now/yesterday; extending the window past where the source has data silently fills the tail with NaN/empty rows and mislabels the output partition."}
{"id":"fail-loud-dont-swallow-systematic-failure","family":"Silent error handling","law":"Don't swallow per-item failures with a bare except/continue or check=False; a SYSTEMATIC error then fires for every item, the job reports success with all-empty/NaN/zero output, and a missing external tool returns an empty result downstream consumes as valid. Catch narrowly and fail loud when the success count is 0."}
{"id":"exclude-nonfinite-or-degenerate-before-use","family":"Data integrity","law":"Exclude or fill NaN/degenerate (zero/missing) values BEFORE any reduction, pivot, or 'latest' selection; one bad value silently poisons a cross-sectional mean/std/z-score, reindex(fill_value) fills only newly-introduced labels not pre-existing internal holes, and the final row may be a degenerate no-data point — the result is silently NaN/skewed/garbage, never an error."}
{"id":"keys-must-be-canonical-complete-and-unique","family":"Key identity","law":"A lookup/storage/recovery key must be in one canonical form, include every dimension that distinguishes its values, and be unique per item; a mis-formatted key silently drops on exact-match, an under-specified key collides so a later write overwrites an earlier one, and a non-unique key collapses distinct positions onto one value — all without raising."}
{"id":"anchor-the-name-match-or-it-grabs-the-wrong-artifact","family":"Artifact selection","law":"A loose startswith/endswith/substring match over artifact names silently selects unintended siblings that share a suffix; anchor the match (full-string/regex) so a base variant cannot collide with its subsetted variants."}
{"id":"positional-consumption-requires-shared-coordinates","family":"Data alignment & indexing","law":"An index or position is only valid in the coordinate system it was computed in; consuming an array by position requires producer and consumer share one ordering, a sub-slice's local index must be rebased before indexing the parent, and a per-step tensor must be addressed by the step index not a weight-sharing schedule's shared index — otherwise every element is silently paired with the wrong row."}
{"id":"derive-runtime-thresholds-from-live-state-not-static-config","family":"Compute, config & diagnosis","law":"Compute runtime decision thresholds from the live measured quantity, not a static config proxy; when the static value diverges from reality the threshold is silently wrong and admits or blocks the wrong items."}
{"id":"quarantine-must-propagate-to-all-consumer-lists","family":"Data integrity","law":"An item flagged as bad must be removed from EVERY downstream consumer list, not merely recorded; a detection that is not enforced leaves the bad item in the working set and silently poisons computation."}
{"id":"sign-convention-must-match-label-semantics","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"An additive tilt/weight/adjustment term must carry the sign that matches the label's semantics; flipping it (1+x vs 1-x, or abs() on a signed edge) pushes the quantity in the opposite direction exactly when it should reverse, with no error."}
{"id":"incremental-export-must-bound-the-window-low-edge","family":"Incremental processing","law":"A periodic incremental export/sync must bound BOTH edges of its window (>= last_cutoff AND < cutoff); filtering only on an open-ended upper cutoff silently re-exports every record before the cutoff on every run. The job still succeeds with a healthy count, so the duplication is invisible until a consumer double-counts."}
{"id":"dont-reapply-a-transform-that-compounds","family":"Pipeline stage boundaries","law":"A transform applied once must not be re-applied — neither by a downstream stage receiving the already-transformed value, nor by a repeated pass that reads its own previous output as the base; re-application compounds silently (2x becomes 4x; a repeated cap decays geometrically toward zero). Reapply only from an immutable baseline captured once."}
{"id":"size-filter-applies-to-the-trade-delta-not-the-target","family":"Order/execution management","law":"A minimum-size (dust) filter must apply to the DELTA between target and current state, not to the target magnitude; filtering on the target skips an item with a tiny target but a large existing position, so the change that needs to happen is silently never made."}
{"id":"reduce-a-shared-freshness-reference-by-max-not-min","family":"Multi-source reduction","law":"A shared catch-up/freshness reference reduced over multiple sources must be the MAX (latest frontier), not the MIN; taking the min gates on the stalest source, so items already covered by the more-advanced sources fall in (min,max] and pass the ts>ref test, getting silently re-admitted and double-counted."}
{"id":"mixin-handler-shadowed-by-base-noop","family":"Method resolution & overriding","law":"When a class mixes a behaviour mixin alongside a base (or a placeholder) that defines a default no-op handler, the MRO decides which runs; if the no-op precedes the real handler it silently shadows it — the event fires, nothing raises, but the side effects never happen. Order the mixin before the base, or delegate the placeholder via super()."}
{"id":"config-resolution-failure-falls-to-silent-defaults","family":"Config & context resolution","law":"A config/context lookup that silently returns empty — a fixed nesting path that doesn't match the object's shape, or a fallback gated on an omitted optional parameter — makes every value fall back to its default with no error, so the job runs with the wrong parameters and raises nothing. Resolve via the shape callers actually pass, and surface an empty resolution."}
{"id":"read-with-the-format-aware-loader-not-raw-bytes","family":"Data integrity","law":"Memory-map/read an on-disk array with the loader that understands the file format (e.g. np.load mmap_mode), not a raw byte mapper with a caller-supplied dtype/shape; a raw mapper reads the format header AS DATA and applies your dtype/shape instead of the stored one, returning a same-shaped array of garbage with no exception."}
{"id":"copy-only-the-fields-you-mean-to-merge","family":"Data integrity","law":"When merging reused/overlapping data into a freshly-built multi-field buffer, restrict the copy to the fields you intend to overwrite; a whole-record assignment also clobbers fields you just computed in that buffer (e.g. a fresh normalized time grid replaced by the source's own, possibly stale-unit, column) with no error."}
{"id":"map-every-case-explicitly-no-default-fallthrough","family":"Compute, config & diagnosis","law":"When a per-case switch converts or dispatches (e.g. a count of bars to a duration by frequency, or data loaded by frequency), give every supported case its own explicit branch and require the discriminator; an unhandled case that falls through to a default silently uses the wrong unit/resolution — the count is honored but in the wrong terms."}
{"id":"parenthesize-the-inline-conditional-in-a-boolean-guard","family":"Operator precedence","law":"An inline conditional (A<B if cond else C) inside an `if` parses as (A<B) if cond else C, NOT a comparison against a ternary value; when the else branch yields a truthy object the guard fires unconditionally. Parenthesize the ternary, or normalize the operands first."}
{"id":"feedback-caliber-must-match-the-realized-objective","family":"Objective & loss shaping","law":"The signal used as feedback to select/weight a model's output must share the exact definition and horizon of the quantity the objective is realized on; a one-step caliber mismatch can flip the measured correlation's sign in mean-reverting regimes, so the optimizer confidently selects choices that lose on the real objective while reporting a positive score."}
{"id":"resolve-graph-output-to-the-last-op-not-a-generic-default","family":"Output resolution","law":"When resolving the final output of a multi-step computation graph, an unset/empty output handle must fall back to the LAST computed operation, not a generic named variable; the generic default silently returns an earlier intermediate, so a streaming/online path diverges from its batch reference."}
{"id":"clamp-the-progress-deficit-before-applying-direction","family":"Order/execution management","law":"A 'remaining work' quantity (target minus done) later multiplied by a direction sign must be clamped to non-negative first; if it goes negative (ahead of schedule) the direction multiply flips its sign and acts in the OPPOSITE direction instead of pausing."}
{"id":"side-effect-hook-must-fire-on-every-branch","family":"Callbacks & side effects","law":"When a side-effect hook records state a downstream consumer depends on, EVERY branch that produces that state must call the hook; if only the common branch invokes it, alternate paths (forcing/prefix/replacement) silently produce the value but never emit it, leaving the consumer missing data with no exception."}
{"id":"use-the-main-not-default-or-total-component-count","family":"Frozen contract & reuse","law":"An operation parameterized by a model's component count (audio codebooks, heads, experts) must read the relevant MAIN count, not a hardcoded default or the TOTAL; a mismatched count silently slices/sizes the wrong sub-tensors with no shape error at that stage."}
{"id":"recompute-or-reset-derived-state-after-a-state-transition","family":"Streaming & resumable state","law":"After a state transition (warmup, snapshot restore, restart), derived/cached state is throwaway or stale: explicitly reset caches (KV-cache holding warmup tokens) and recompute derived/cross-sectional quantities before first real use, or the run silently attends over garbage or uses stale derived values that no longer satisfy their constraint."}
{"id":"project-hidden-states-through-the-output-head-for-logits","family":"Architecture wiring","law":"Logits are the output head (final norm + vocab projection) applied to the transformer's hidden states, not the raw hidden states; returning the hidden state as logits yields a wrong-dimensioned distribution and a garbage argmax, with no error."}
{"id":"flatten-per-job-lists-with-extend-not-append","family":"Concurrency & aggregation","law":"When aggregating per-job partial outputs where each job returns a LIST for a key, merge with extend (flatten), not append; append nests each job's list so the combined result has the wrong shape, and the call still returns successfully, leaving consumers to silently iterate lists instead of items."}
{"id":"clone-workers-must-decorrelate-the-stream","family":"Concurrency & aggregation","law":"Cloned dataloader/sampler workers each replay identical index state, so the concatenated global stream clumps or duplicates instead of following the intended order; offset each worker by its id and stride by the worker count."}
{"id":"byte-fallback-tokens-need-byte-level-reassembly","family":"Frozen contract & reuse","law":"A byte-fallback tokenizer's decode contract is to reassemble raw bytes and utf-8-decode once; string-concatenating token surfaces silently emits literal <0x..> garbage for every character outside the base vocab."}
{"id":"weight-running-average-interpolation-by-snapshot-count","family":"Regime transfer & init","law":"When interpolating two running-averaged checkpoints, weight them by the count of snapshots actually folded into the average (step // update_period), not the raw global step — the running average only refreshes every update_period steps, so the raw step over-weights it."}
{"id":"no-survivorship-in-universe-selection","family":"Information set & leakage","law":"A shared resource (universe/schema/feature set) that must serve many consumers each with its own required element set must cover the UNION of all needs, not the INTERSECTION; intersecting silently keeps only elements present in EVERY consumer and biases the set toward survivors that persist across all periods."}
{"id":"operate-on-the-axis-that-means-sequence","family":"Architecture wiring","law":"Reduce or index by an axis's MEANING (the sequence axis, the channel axis), not a hardcoded leading position; a fixed axis 0 or a length op on the wrong axis is shape-compatible but silently operates on a batch/sibling dim, desyncing the tensor from its labels with no error."}

# --- promoted from the `proposals` + `kimi` meta-projects (record/UI/host-integration laws) ---
{"id": "append-only-record", "family": "Record & audit", "law": "A record that exists to preserve history must be append-only: never delete or rewrite an entry — give it a terminal status and an outcome note instead. Mutating or rolling back an entry silently destroys exactly the institutional memory the record exists to keep."}
{"id": "flat-independent-collection", "family": "Record & audit", "law": "When many peer items must coexist, model them as a flat, independent collection with no privileged 'active' singleton; forcing one active item (and overwriting it on each change) silently discards every other item and couples things that should be independent."}
{"id": "status-at-the-right-altitude", "family": "State & lifecycle", "law": "Lifecycle state belongs at the altitude of the thing it describes: an aggregate's status (draft/accepted/superseded/abandoned) is a different axis from its components' status. Reusing the item-level status field for the aggregate conflates two independent lifecycles and the aggregate's real state becomes unrepresentable."}
{"id": "lineage-pointer", "family": "State & lifecycle", "law": "An append-only history is only navigable if each entry records what it supersedes (an explicit parent/supersedes pointer); plain timestamp order cannot express branch or replacement relationships, so without the pointer the lineage of versions is silently lost."}
{"id": "overview-first", "family": "Reporting & UI", "law": "A surface that manages many items must present an overview — list, status, filter across ALL items — before drilling into any one (overview, then zoom, then detail); jumping straight to a single item's page with no index hides the collection and makes it unmanageable."}
{"id": "diff-not-dump", "family": "Reporting & UI", "law": "To compare two versions, surface the DELTA — what was added, changed, dropped, restatused — not two full dumps side by side; a dump makes the reader recompute the diff by eye, so the actual change hides in the noise."}
{"id": "enforcement-needs-a-target", "family": "Guards & enforcement", "law": "An enforcer (guard, doorman, validator) acts ON a specific subject; remove the singleton it keyed off (e.g. the one 'active' context) without giving it a new explicit target and it silently has nothing to bind to and goes quiet — the rules still exist but enforce nothing."}
{"id": "backward-compatible-migration", "family": "Migration & compatibility", "law": "A schema or model change must let existing artifacts keep working — migrate them in place or treat each as the first instance of the new shape, with reads degrading gracefully on absent fields; a change that requires re-authoring everything old silently breaks every existing artifact."}
{"id": "host-channel-fit", "family": "Host integration", "law": "Deliver each signal through a channel the host actually consumes; a capability the host lacks (e.g. context injection on a block-only host) must be folded into a channel it does have, or explicitly dropped. Emitting on a channel the host never reads silently sends the signal nowhere."}
{"id": "fail-open-never-exit-block", "family": "Guards & enforcement", "law": "A guard/hook wrapping a host must fail OPEN: any internal error, timeout, or missing piece must ALLOW the action, and blocking must go through one explicit narrow channel only. A guard that can fail closed can lock the whole system on its own bug — the worst failure mode for a safety layer."}
{"id": "report-as-gate", "family": "Guards & enforcement", "law": "An output can be gated for quality wherever the host re-invokes the turn with the rejection reason fed back in: block once, reason becomes the next input, guarded against re-entry. Without that re-feed path a gate can only reject, never get the output rewritten."}
